revision.text:
'''Operation PBFORTUNE''', also known as '''Operation FORTUNE''', was the name of a covert [[United States]] operation to overthrow the democratically elected Guatemalan President [[Jacobo Árbenz]] in 1952. The operation was authorized by US President [[Harry Truman]] and planned by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]. The United Fruit Company had lobbied intensively for the overthrow, because the landmark [[Decree 900|land reform]] enacted by Árbenz threatened its economic interests. The coup attempt was also motivated by US fears that the government of [[Jacobo Árbenz]] was being influenced by communists. It involved providing weapons to the exiled Guatemalan military officer [[Carlos Castillo Armas]], who was to lead an invasion from Nicaragua. The coup was planned with the knowledge and support of [[Anastasio Somoza García]], [[Rafael Leonidas Trujillo]] and [[Marcos Pérez Jiménez]], the US-backed right-wing dictators of Nicaragua, Dominican Republic and Venezuela respectively, as well as the [[United Fruit Company]]. However, the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] discovered that details of the plan had become too widely known.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|pp=29–31}} US Secretary of State [[Dean Acheson]] was worried that the coup attempt would damage the image of the US, which had committed to a policy of non-intervention, and so terminated the operation.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} Operation PBFORTUNE was a precursor to [[Operation PBSUCCESS]], the covert operation that toppled Árbenz and ended the [[Guatemalan Revolution]] in 1954.{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=118–122}}

==Background==
[[File:Arbenz 1945.jpg|thumb|Border|right|220px|alt=File photo of Árbenz|Guatemalan President Jacobo Árbenz, whose landmark agrarian reform benefited 500,000 people.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=149–164}}]]
{{Main article|Guatemalan Revolution}}
From the late 19th century until 1944 [[Guatemala]] was governed by a series of authoritarian rulers. Between 1898 and 1920 [[Manuel Estrada Cabrera]] granted significant concessions to the [[United Fruit Company]], as well as dispossessing many [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas#Guatemala|indigenous peoples]] of their communal land.{{sfn|Forster|2001|pp=12–15}}{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=10–11}} Under [[Jorge Ubico]], who ruled as a dictator between 1931 and 1944, this process was intensified, with the institution of brutal labor regulations and the establishment of a [[police state]].{{sfn|Forster|2001|pp=29–32}}{{sfn|Cullather|1999|pp=9–10}}

In June 1944, a popular pro-democracy movement led by university students and labor organizations forced Ubico to resign.{{sfn|Forster|2001|p=86}} Ubico handed over power to a military junta{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|p=27}} that was toppled in a military coup led by [[Jacobo Árbenz]] in October 1944, an event also known as the "October Revolution."{{sfn|Immerman|1982|p=42}} The coup leaders called for open elections, which were won by [[Juan José Arévalo]], a progressive professor of philosophy who had become the face of the popular movement. He implemented a moderate program of social reform, including a widely successful literacy campaign and largely free elections, although illiterate women were not given the vote, and communist parties were banned.{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=46–49}}

Following the end of Arévalo's highly popular presidency in 1951, Jacobo Árbenz was elected to the presidency.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=11}}{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=73–84}} He continued the reforms of Arévalo, and also began an ambitious land reform program, known as [[Decree 900]]. Under it, the uncultivated portions of large land-holdings were expropriated in return for compensation,{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=149–164}} and redistributed to poverty-stricken agricultural laborers.{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=64–67}} Due to the political climate of the [[cold war]], the US was already predisposed to see the socialist policies of the democratically elected Arévalo and Árbenz as communists. This conception was strengthened by Arévalo' support for the [[Caribbean Legion]], and by the 1950s the US government was considering overthrowing the Guatemalan president.{{sfn|Schlesinger|Kinzer|1999|p=72–77}}{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=82–100}}

The attitude of the United States was also influenced by the [[Monroe Doctrine]], a philosophy of foreign policy articulated by [[James Monroe]] in 1823,{{sfn|Streeter|2000|p=8}}{{sfn|Gilderhus|2006}} and which justified the maintenance of US hegemony in the region.{{sfn|Streeter|2000|pp=8–10}} The stated aim of the doctrine was to maintain order and stability, and to make certain that access to resources and markets was not limited.{{sfn|Gilderhus|2006}} Historian Mark Gilderhus states that the doctrine also contained racially condescending language, which likened Latin American countries to fighting children.{{sfn|Gilderhus|2006}} The US government did not need to engage in military interventions in Guatemala to enforce this hegemony, given the presence of military rulers friendly to the US;{{sfn|Streeter|2000|pp=8–10}} however, the doctrine was used to justify the coup in 1954.{{sfn|Smith|1995|p=6}}

==Planning==
