===Somoza's visit===
In May 1952, Jacobo Árbenz enacted [[Decree 900]], the official title of the Guatemalan agrarian reform law.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|p=228}} The law convinced the US government that the Guatemalan government was being influenced by communists.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|p=228}} Approximately 500,000 people benefited from the decree.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=149–164}} However, the [[United Fruit Company]] lost several hundred thousand acres of its uncultivated land to this law, and the compensation it received was based on the grossly undervalued price that it had presented to the Guatemalan government for tax purposes.{{sfn|Schlesinger|Kinzer|1999|p=72–77}} The company therefore intensified its lobbying against the Guatemalan government in Washington.{{sfn|Schlesinger|Kinzer|1999|p=72–77}} The CIA started to explore the notion of lending support to detractors and opponents of Árbenz. [[Walter Bedell Smith]], the director of Central Intelligence, ordered [[J. C. King]], the chief of the Western Hemisphere Division, to examine whether dissident Guatemalan's could topple the Árbenz government, if they had support from the dictatorships in Central America.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=27}} At this point the US government was approached by [[Anastasio Somoza García]], the US-backed dictator of Nicaragua. Somoza had been on a private visit to the United States, during which he made public speeches praising the United States, and was awarded a medal by New York City.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=228–229}}{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}} During a meeting with Truman and his senior staff, Somoza stated that if he were given the weapons, he would "clean up Guatemala."{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=228–229}} Truman's personal military adviser, Major General [[Harry H. Vaughan]], persuaded Truman to explore the opportunity further, and Truman asked [[Walter Bedell Smith]], director of Intelligence, to follow up.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}}

===Carlos Castillo Armas===
Although the proposal was not taken seriously at the time, US Colonel Cornelius Mara flew back to Nicaragua with Somoza to further explore the idea.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=228–229}} Somoza persuaded Mara that the plan was feasible, and Mara returned to the US and gave Truman a favorable report.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Smith also sent a Spanish-speaking engineer {{efn|''Secret History'', by [[Nick Cullather]], is based on declassified documents from the US Central Intelligence Agency. Several of these documents are redacted, leaving out certain information, redactions which have been reproduced in Cullather's text.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=2}} The name of the engineer dispatched to Guatemala has been redacted.}} to contact exiled Guatemalan army officer Carlos Castillo Armas and his fellow dissidents, who were in Honduras and Guatemala.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}} Castillo Armas had been expelled from the country in 1949 following a [[Guatemalan Revolution#1949 coup attempt|failed coup attempt]] against Arévalo.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=59–69}} Castillo Armas had been a ''protégé'' of [[Francisco Javier Arana]], and had risen in the military to become the head of the military academy of Guatemala by 1949.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=12}} Following the failed coup of 1949, Árbenz had him imprisoned under doubtful charges until December 1949, when he came to the attention of the CIA. A month later, a CIA officer found him attempting to get weapons from Somoza and Trujillo.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=12}} He met with the CIA a few more times before November 1950, when he launch a brazen attack against Matamoros, and was jailed for it, before bribing his way out of prison.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|pp=12–13}} Castillo Armas told the CIA that he had the support of the Civil Guard (''Guardia Civil''), the garrison at [[Quezaltenango]], and the commander of [[Matamoros (disambiguation)|Matamoros]], the largest fortress in the capital.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=12}} The engineer dispatched by the CIA also informed them that Castillo Armas had the financial backing of Somoza and Trujillo.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}} Truman thereupon authorized Operation PBFORTUNE, but according to Historian [[Piero Gleijeses]], did not inform the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]], or secretary of state [[Dean Acheson]] of the plan.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Based upon an examination of declassified documents, however, historian [[Nick Cullather]] has stated that the CIA did, in fact, seek State Department approval before authorizing the plan, and that undersecretary of state David Bruce provided explicit approval for it.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=29}} [[Allen Dulles]] had previously contacted State Department official Thomas Mann and, the [[Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs|assistant secretary of state for Inter-American affairs]] Edward G. Miller. Both these individuals had stated that they wanted a new government in Guatemala even if it involved the use of force, but did not explicitly tell Dulles to take any action to topple Árbenz.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=29}}

===The plot===
The details of the plot were finalized over the next few weeks by the CIA, the United Fruit Company, and Somoza. The coup plotters contacted [[Rafael Leonidas Trujillo]] and [[Marcos Pérez Jiménez]], the US-supported right-wing dictators of the Dominican Republic and Venezuela, respectively. The two dictators were supportive of the plan, and agreed to contribute some funding.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Although PBFORTUNE was officially approved on September 9, 1952, various planning steps had been taken earlier in the year. In January 1952, officers in the CIA's [[National Clandestine Service|Directorate of Plans]] compiled a list of "top flight Communists whom the new government would desire to eliminate immediately in the event of a successful anti-Communist coup."{{sfn|Haines|1995}} The CIA plan called for the assassination of over 58 Guatemalans, as well as the arrest of many others.{{sfn|Haines|1995}} The plan was to involve no direct intervention from the US. It was instead to have been carried out by Castillo Armas.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}}

When contacted by the CIA agent dispatched by Walter Bedell Smith, Castillo Armas had proposed a battle-plan to gain CIA support. This plan involved three forced invading Guatemala from Mexico, Honduras, and El Salvador.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}} These invasions were supposed to be led by internal rebellions.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=28}}{{efn|The name of the individual who was supposed to lead the internal uprisings has been redacted in the CIA documents.}} King formulated a plan to provide Castillo Armas with $225,000 as well as weaponry and transportation. His plan also suggested that Somoza and [[Juan Manuel Galvez]], the President of Honduras, be persuaded to provide air support, in addition to other help.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=29}} The proposal went to [[Allen Dulles]], deputy director of the CIA. It also emphasized the relatively small role that the CIA was supposed to play, and stated that the plot would probably go ahead without the CIA's support, but would likely fail and lead to a crackdown on anti-Communist forces.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=29}}

==Execution and termination==
[[File:Dean Acheson.jpg|thumb|US Secretary of State Dean Acheson, whose intervention ended the operation.]]
The plan was put into motion in autumn 1952 by the CIA.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|p=230}} J. C. King had gotten hold of weapons from the stock of those that had been confiscated by port authorities in the city of New York. These included 250 rifles, 380 pistols, 64 machine guns, and 4500 grenades.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|pp=29–31}}{{efn|Details of other types of weapons have been redacted in the CIA documents.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=29}}}} The United Fruit Company lent one of its freighters to the CIA. The freighter was specially refitted and loaded with weapons in New Orleans under the guise of agricultural machinery.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|p=230}} It was scheduled to sail to Nicaragua in early October 1952.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} The CIA had encouraged Somoza and Galvez to provide support to Castillo Armas' forces. Somoza, however, informed several government officials across Central America of the CIA's role in the coup attempt. Somoza's son Tacho, for instance, casually asked Edward Miller whether "the machinery" was on its way at a meeting in Panama.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}}

Accounts of the final termination of the coup attempt vary between historians. Piero Gleijeses stated that while the freighter was on its way to Nicaragua, a CIA employee went to Edward Miller, and asked him to sign a document on behalf of the munitions department.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Miller refused, and instead showed the document to his superiors, who in turn informed Dean Acheson.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Gleijeses writes that Acheson immediately spoke to Truman as a result of this document, and the operation was cut short.{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} Nick Cullather writes that due to Somoza spreading the word about the coup, the state department decided that the cover of the operation had been lost.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} Other diplomats began to learn of the operation, and on 8 October Dean Acheson summoned Walter Bedell Smith and called off the operation.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}}

Acheson was particularly worried that allowing the details of the coup to go public would damage the image of the US. The [[Inter-American Treaty of Reciprocal Assistance|Rio Pact of 1947]] had created the [[Organization of American States]], or OAS, and this body had obtained jurisdiction over regional disputes from the [[United Nations]].{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} In order to achieve this, the US had also committed to a policy of non-intervention in the internal affairs of other countries. If PBFORTUNE had become public knowledge, the fact that the US was supporting an invasion of a country that was also a member of the OAS would have represented a huge setback to US policy.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} Thus the state department promptly ended the operation when they became aware that its cover was blown.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}}

==Aftermath==
{{Further information|1954 Guatemalan coup d'état|Guatemalan Civil War}}
The termination of the operation caught the CIA by surprise, and King quickly attempted to salvage what he could.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} The freighter was redirected to Panama, where the arms were unloaded;{{sfn|Gleijeses|1991|pp=229–230}} King kept the weapons there in the hope that the project could be rejuvenated.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=31}} Castillo Armas was paid a retainer of $3000 a week, which allowed him to maintain a small force. The CIA remained in contact with him, and continued to provide support to the rebels.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=32}} King continued to explore the CIA's ability to move arms around Central America without the approval of the state department.{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=32}}

In November 1952, [[Dwight Eisenhower]] was elected president of the US. Eisenhower's campaign had promised a more hawkish stance against communism. Many senior figures in his cabinet, including [[John Foster Dulles]] and his brother [[Allen Dulles]] had close connections to the United Fruit Company, which made Eisenhower predisposed to supporting Árbenz' overthrow more strongly than Truman.{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=122–127}}{{sfn|Cullather|1999|p=32}} In June 1954, the US trained and funded an invasion force led by Castillo Armas, backed by an intense campaign of psychological warfare by the CIA.{{sfn|Immerman|1982|pp=161–170}} Jacobo Árbenz resigned on 27 June 1954, ending the Guatemalan Revolution.{{sfn|Schlesinger|Kinzer|1999|pp=190–204}} From 1954 onwards Guatemala was ruled by a series of US-backed military dictators, leading to the [[Guatemalan Civil War]]. {{sfn|Grandin|2000|p=28}} 200,000 civilians were killed in the war, and numerous human rights violations committed, including massacres of civilian populations, rape, aerial bombardment, and [[Forced disappearance#Guatemala|forced disappearances]].{{sfn|McAllister|2010}} 93% of these violations were committed by the United States-backed military, which included a genocidal scorched-earth campaign against the indigenous [[Maya people|Maya population]] in the 1980s.{{sfn|McAllister|2010}}

